      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Hey! That's a great question, and you're right to wonder why scaling matters when the model \"sees\" big numbers. The issue is that most of your features are between 0 and 1, while your income column is up to 200,000. If you don't scale it, the model might get confused because the income values are so much larger than the other features. It's like trying to compare a tiny goblin to a giant dragon without adjusting their sizes!\n\nIn machine learning, algorithms often use distance-based calculations (like in KNN or neural networks) where the scale of the input matters. If one feature is 200,000 and another is 0.5, the model might think the income feature is infinitely more important just because of its magnitude. Scaling brings all features to a similar range, so the model can learn from them equally.\n\nThink of it like a goblin trying to fit into a tiny hat. If the goblin is too big, it won't fit, and the hat might fall off. Scaling is like shrinking the goblin to fit perfectly into the hat. Without scaling, the model might focus too much on the income feature and",
